      "is_answer_order_important": false,
      "stimulus_html": "",
      "stem_html": "<p>Carboxylic acids having a second carbonyl group two atoms away lose CO<sub>2</sub> <i>(decarboxylate)</i> through an intermediate enolate ion when treated with base. Write the mechanism of this decarboxylation reaction using curved arrows to show the electron flow in each step.</p>\n<img class=\"scaled-down\" src=\"https://exercises.openstax.org/rails/active_storage/blobs/proxy/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaHBBdDRXIiwiZXhwIjpudWxsLCJwdXIiOiJibG9iX2lkIn19--9b4cb91f1eefde88bd2fad48ac0419c9137c4426/OChem_20_EC_041.jpg\" alt=\"Conversion of 3-oxobutanoic acid on reaction with aqueous sodium hydroxide to a three-carbon enolate ion and carbon dioxide. Further reaction with water produces propan-2-one.\">\n",
